_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere are significant variations in how healthcare systems and health professionals are regulated globally. One feature that they increasingly have in common is an emphasis on the value of including members of the public in quality assurance processes. While many argue that this will help better serve the public interest, others question how far the changing regulatory reform agenda is still dominated by medical interests. Bringing together leading academics worldwide, this collection compares and critically examines the ways in which different countries are regulating healthcare in general, and health professions in particular, in the interest of users and the wider public. It is the first book in the Sociology of Health Professions series.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aPublic health laws. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAhmed, Humayun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllsop, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlmeida, Joana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarros, Nelson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBismark, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Adalsteinn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalnan, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChamberlain, John Martyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChamberlain, John Martyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDent, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDent